If I optimize “paper airplane,” the map works differently than if I optimize “navigation.”

If I insist the paper airplane will still reliably guide me across the wilderness, reality pushes back.

That connects strongly to your “truth priorities” phrasing.

People often prioritize different truths simultaneously:

* precision truth (“What is objectively happening?”)
* strategic truth (“What framing helps accomplish the goal?”)
* social truth (“What preserves trust?”)
* symbolic truth (“What meaning does this carry?”)
* local truth (“What works here under these constraints?”)
* invariant truth (“What survives translation across contexts?”)

